Preheat your oven to 200°C. Pop a #large saucepan{} of water onto boil with
@salt{0.5%tsp}. Trim the @green beans{150%g}. Peel the @potatoes{450%g} and
chop into ½cm thick discs. Add to the water and cook gently until the potatoes
have softened but are not cooked through, ~{6-8%minutes}. Meanwhile, halve,
peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced). Peel and
grate the @garlic{2%cloves} (or use a garlic press). When the potatoes are
cooked, drain into a #colander{} and allow to steam for a couple of minutes.

Once the potatoes are drained, lay half the potato slices in an appropriately
sized #ovenproof dish{}. Set aside. Heat a splash of @oil{a splash} in a
#frying pan{} over a medium-high heat. Add the onion and cook until softened and
lightly browned, ~{5-6%minutes}. Add half the garlic and cook for ~{1%minute}.
Pour in the @water for the gratin{75%ml}, @vegetable stock powder{1} and
@creme fraiche{150%g}. Bring to the boil pour onto the potatoes in the dish.
Arrange the remaining potatoes on top. Bake the gratin in the oven until the
potatoes are cooked through and top is golden, ~{25-30%minutes}.

10 mins before the gratin is cooked, heat a drizzle of @oil{a drizzle} in a
frying pan on high heat. Season the @21 day aged British sirloin steaks{2} with
@salt{} and @pepper{}. When the oil is hot, lay the steaks in the pan and brown
for ~{1%minute} on each side. Lower the heat slightly and cook for another
~{1-2%minutes} on each side for medium rare.

> TIP: Cook for 1-2 mins more if you like it more cooked.

> IMPORTANT: The steak is safe to eat when the outside is browned.

Set aside to a #plate{} to rest wrapped in #foil{}. Don't wash your pan, you
need it later for your sauce.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{a drizzle} in another frying pan on medium high heat.
Add the green beans, season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and stir fry for
~{2%minutes} then add the remaining garlic and cook, stirring, for
~{1%minute}. Add a splash of @water{a splash}, cover with foil and cook for
~{3-4%minutes}, until just tender.

While the beans cook, add the @water for the jus{150%ml} to the now empty steak
frying pan with the @red wine jus paste{1} over medium high heat. Stir to
dissolve, bring to the boil then simmer for ~{1-2%minutes}. Add a splash of
@water{}, @steak resting juices{} to loosen if you like.

Divide the gratin between your plates, serve with the steak and green beans
drizzled with the jus. Enjoy!